1c)

In lecture we discussed that regardless of the labels or classes associated with the binary response, we can encode the outcome as y = 1 if the "event" is observed and y = 0 if the "non_event" is observed. You will encode the output with this 0/1 encoding.

The ifelse() function can help you perform this operation. The ifelse() function is a one-line if-statement which operates similar to the IF function in Excel. The basic syntax is:

ifelse(<conditional statement to check>, <value if TRUE>, <value if FALSE>)

Thus, the user must specify a condition to check as the first argument to the ifelse() function. The second argument is the value to return if the conditional statement is TRUE, and the second argument is the value to return if the conditional statement is FALSE.

You can use the ifelse() statement within a mutate() call to create a new column in the model_pred_df data set.

The code chunk below provides an example using the first 10 rows from the iris data set which is loaded with base R. The Sepal.Width variable is compared to a value of 3.5. If Sepal.Width is greater than 3.5 the new variable, width_factor, is set equal to "greater than". However, if it is less than 3.5 the new variable is set to "less than".

iris %>% 
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  select(starts_with("Sepal"), Species) %>% 
  mutate(width_factor = ifelse(Sepal.Width > 3.5,

As mentioned before, the steps taken to calculate the Sensitivity and FPR for each threshold value were not the most efficient. In fact, its quite tedious to have to repeat those actions multiple times. It would be more appropriate to define a function to calculate them for us! That way we do not resort to the error prone task of copying and pasting!

You were not required to use a function when you calculated the ROC curve. The code chunk below is provided if you would like to learn more about programming the tidy way. A function, calc_confusion_metrics(), is defined which consists of 2 input arguments. The first, threshold, is a threshold value, and the second, df, is a data set. The data set is assumed to have a column named pred_class and obs_class with the event of interest labeled 'event' and the non-event labeled as 'non_event'. After counting the combinations of pred_class and obs_class, the calc_confusion_metrics() function changes the names and labels to be consistent with the more general confusion matrix terms, 'T', 'F', 'P', and 'N'. Several data reshaping steps are performed (the right_join() and tidyr::spread() function calls) in order to make sure all four confusion matrix cells are present. This is done because as we saw in lecture if the threshold is very low the classifications would never result in a False-Negative or True-Negative. The last step in the work flow is to calculate the different performance metrics associated with the confusion matrix that we discussed in lecture.

calc_confusion_metrics <- function(threshold, df)
{
  df %>% 
    mutate(pred_class = ifelse(pred_prob > threshold, "event", "non_event")) %>% 
    count(obs_class, pred_class) %>% 
    # rename to more general confusion matrix terms
    mutate(pred_class_name = ifelse(pred_class == "event", "P", "N"),
           pred_correct = ifelse(pred_class == obs_class, "T", "F")) %>% 
    tidyr::unite(confusion_cell,
                 c("pred_correct", "pred_class_name"),
                 sep = "",
                 remove = FALSE) %>% 
    select(n, confusion_cell) %>% 
    # check all 4 confusion cells are there
    right_join(tibble::tibble(confusion_cell = c("TP", "FN", "FP", "TN"),
                              confusion_name = c("True-Positive", 
                                                 "False-Negative", 
                                                 "False-Positive",
                                                 "True-Negative")),
               by = "confusion_cell") %>% 
    mutate(n = ifelse(is.na(n), 0, n)) %>%
    mutate(threshold = threshold) %>% 
    select(-confusion_name) %>%
    tidyr::spread(confusion_cell, n) %>%
    # calculate metrics
    mutate(Accuracy = (TN + TP) / (TN + TP + FN + FP),
           Sensitivity = TP / (TP + FN),
           Specificity = TN / (FP + TN),
           FPR = 1 - Specificity)
}

The calc_confusion_metrics() function has threshold as the first argument to enable functionally looping over different threshold values using the purrr library. We will learn more about purrr as we progress through the semester, but I prefer purrr to defining for-loops. The code chunk below uses purrr::map_dfr() to loop over the three threshold values of interest (0.3, 0.5, 0.7) and assemble the result into a data.frame (tibble). The result is piped into ggplot() where the simple 3 point ROC curve is created as before.

purrr::map_dfr(c(0.3, 0.5, 0.7), 
               calc_confusion_metrics, 
               df = model_pred_df) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = 1 - Specificity,
                       y = Sensitivity)) +
  geom_point(size = 7.5) +

4a)

Are the levels of the binary outcome, y, balanced?

SOLUTION

We can check if the binary outcome is balanced several ways. First, we can display the counts per level (unique value) with the dplyr::count() function.

df %>% count(y)

##   y             n
##   <fct>     <int>

As we see above, the counts are quite similar and thus the outcome is balanced. We can also calculate the proportion per level if we would prefer to look at the relative frequency of each level.

df %>%

df %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = y)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_bw()

df %>% 
  summarise(mean(y == 'event'))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   `mean(y == "event")`
##                  <dbl>
## 1                0.484

Lastly, we could just use the mean() function with the conditional test df$y == 'event'.

mean( df$y == 'event' )
## [1] 0.483871

The mean() function sums the number of rows that the y equals 'event' and divides by the total number of observations. This is confirmed in the code chunk below.

sum( df$y == 'event' ) / nrow(df)
## [1] 0.483871

Any of the above approaches demonstrate that the two levels of the binary outcome are nearly perfectly balanced.

4d)

You are going to train 8 binary classifiers in this problem. The different models will use different features derived from the 4 inputs. The 8 models must have the following features:

  • model 1: linear additive features all inputs
  • model 2: linear features and quadratic features all inputs
  • model 3: linear features and quadratic features just inputs 1 and 2
  • model 4: linear features and quadratic features just inputs 1 and 3
  • model 5: linear features and quadratic features just inputs 1 and 4
  • model 6: linear features and quadratic features just inputs 2 and 3
  • model 7: linear features and quadratic features just inputs 2 and 4
  • model 8: linear features and quadratic features just inputs 3 and 4

Model 1 is the conventional linear method for binary classification. All other models have linear and quadratic terms to allow capturing non-linear relationships with the event probability (just how that works will be discussed later in the semester). Model 2 creates the features from all four inputs. The remaining 6 models use the combinations of just two of the inputs. This scheme is trying to identify the best possible set of inputs to model the binary outcome in a step-wise like fashion. This is not an efficient way to identify the best set of features to use. Later in the semester, we will learn a much more efficient modeling approach that performs this operation for us!

You must complete the 8 code chunks below. Use the formula interface to create the features in the model, analogous to the approach used in the previous assignment. You must specify the method argument in the train() function to be "glm". You must specify the remaining arguments to train() accordingly.

The variable names and comments within the code chunks specify which model you are working with.

NOTE: The models are trained in separate code chunks that way you can run each model separately from the others.

SOLUTION

We could type the formula for model 1 as y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + x4. However, we can use the shortcut operator, ., to create all linear additive features because the data set, df, contains only inputs and the binary outcome. Thus, we can specify the formula as y ~ .. The short cut operator, ., will use all columns except the defined response (the variable to the left of the tilde) as linear features for the model. The short cut operator can streamline the amount we need to code. However, it is important to know how the features are used in a model. More advanced methods, such as tree-based methods, can use the short cut operator in the formula interface and still create non-linear and interaction features from those inputs. We will see how those kinds of models work later in the semester. For now, we can view the short cut operator as using all of the remaining variables in the data set as inputs to the model.

Model 1 is trained and assessed below using our desired resampling scheme. Although not required, the preProcess argument is specified such that the inputs are standardized before training each model. You were not required to do this for this assignment. The preProcess argument is included below to introduce how caret can pre-process the features to the model.

### model 1
set.seed(2021)
mod_1_acc <- train(y ~ ., data = df,
                   method = 'glm',
                   metric = metric_acc,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                   trControl = ctrl_acc)

The model with linear additive features has an averaged Accuracy of about 76%. Because the empirical proportion of the event is close to 50%, we can say this model is performing better than random guessing. As discussed in lecture, we do not want to look at the average point estimate in isolation. We want to consider the uncertainty on the average. The uncertainty on the average is represented in the figure below with the 95% confidence interval. Models with overlapping confidence intervals do not have statistically significant average performance values. As we see below mod_3, the model with linear and quadratic features of just the first two inputs (x1 and x2) has the highest averaged Accuracy. The 95% confidence intervals overlap with model 2 which has linear and quadratic features associated with all inputs. Although we have overlap in the confidence intervals between the two models, mod_3 is the simpler of the two! We would prefer to work with a simpler model with fewer features and thus mod_3 would be selected as the best model.

dotplot(acc_results, metric = 'Accuracy')

The default plotting options for dotplot() show the 95% confidence interval. The figure above shows we only have separation (no overlap) on the average results between a group of models consisting of 3, 2, 6, 7, and 1 from another group of models including models 4, 5, and 8. The group with lower performance do not include input 2. The worst performing model, mod_8, does not include either input 1 or 2. Performance therefore gets worse when the first two inputs are not included! Thus, we can conclude that the first two inputs are important with input 2 being the most important.

It can be helpful to reach such conclusions by visualizing both the \(\pm\) 1 and \(\pm\) 2 standard error intervals on the average. This helps us see which models are considered by the one-standard error rule as being within the margin of error of the best model. You did not have to do this, but the code chunk below shows how to extract all resample results and visualize the standard error intervals on the mean with ggplots stat_summary() function. The \(\pm\) 1 standard error interval on the average is shown in red and the \(\pm\) 2 standard error interval is shown in black. As shown below, mod_6, mod_7, and mod_1 appear to have average Accuracy values less than one-standard error below the highest averaged Accuracy. The one-standard error rule would therefore recommend not focusing on those models.

as.data.frame(acc_results, method = 'Accuracy') %>% 
  pivot_longer(!c("Resample")) %>% 
  mutate(name = forcats::fct_reorder(name, value, mean)) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = name, y = value)) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = 'mean_se',
               fun.args = list(mult = 2),
               size = 1.25) +

               fun.args = list(mult = 1),

Why does the sensitivity have values at or near 1 when the .threshold is so low?

The resample hold-out test set predictions for mod_1_roc are pipped into the roc_curve() function below. The forward pipe operator, %>%, assigns the piped object as the first argument to the function. We then only need to specify the second and third arguments to roc_curve(). The second argument is the reference or observed outcome and the third argument is the model predicted probability of the event. Thus, the second argument is set to obs and the third argument is set to event. The portion of the ROC curve printed to screen shows us the specificity and sensitivity for very low thresholds. For example, the second row is a threshold of less than 0.005! With such a low threshold as long as the model predicts a probability greater than 0.5% the outcome will be classified as the event! The Sensitivity is very high because it is easy to classify the event with such a low threshold. The classification is always set to event which is why the True Positive Rate is 100%. However, we see that that Specificity (the True Negative Rate) is zero when the threshold is that low. This means the model is always wrong at classifying the non-event when the threshold is that low.

compile_all_model_preds <- function(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, m6, m7, m8)
{
  purrr::map2_dfr(list(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, m6, m7, m8),
                  as.character(seq_along(list(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, m6, m7, m8))),
                  function(ll, lm){
                    ll$pred %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
                      select(obs, event, Resample) %>% 
                      mutate(model_name = lm)
                  })
}

Your pred_test_1 object should have 2 columns. The event column gives the predicted probability that y == 'event' and the non_event column stores the predicted probability that y == 'non_event'.

What is the relationship between the values in the event column and the non_event column?

SOLUTION

The event columns stores the probability of the event and the non_event column stores the probability of the non-event. The outcome is binary and thus those are the only two values associated with the outcome. The outcome must equal one of those two values and thus the sum of the event probability and the non-event probability equals 1.

As discussed in lecture, the calibration curve bins or lumps the predicted probability into uniformly spaced intervals. The empirical proportion of the event within each bin must be calculated. Thus, you need to convert the numeric predicted probability into a discrete or categorical variable.

A simple, yet effective, approach for categorizing a continuous variable is the cut() function. The cut function is demonstrated in the code chunk below. The variable x is a column within a tibble (a dataframe). The x variable consists of integers between 0 and 100. 7a)

Calculate the empirical proportion of events within each predicted probability bin associated with model 1. Although you are free to perform the calculations however you like, the results should be stored in a tibble (dataframe) named my_calcurve_1 object. Your object should have columns for the pred_bin, the event proportion in the bin named prop_event, and the midpoint of the bin named mid_bin. Your my_calcurve_1 object can have other columns, but those three columns are required.

SOLUTION

There are many ways to go about calculating the event proportion per bin. You do not have to perform the same procedure I show below, but your results must the same as those presented here. The operation is quite simple to perform with the group_by() and summarize() functions from dplyr. These are both common and yet important operations in any data analysis project.

Calculating the event proportion is simple. We just need to use the mean() function with the summarize() call. The bin mid point though is a little trickier and requires planning. A simple approach requires calculating the maximum and minimum event probability in each bin and then using a mutate() call to average them together. This is not equal to the true bin midpoint, but is acceptable for this assignment.

my_calcurve_1 <- test_df_1_b %>% 
  group_by(pred_bin) %>% 
  summarise(num_obs = n(),
            num_events = sum(y == 'event'),
            prop_event = mean(y == 'event'),
            min_prob = min(event),
            max_prob = max(event),
            .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  mutate(mid_bin = 0.5*(min_prob + max_prob))

The my_calccurve_1 tibble has just 10 rows, one row for each bin. As you can see below, the minimum and maximum predicted event probabilities are close to the bin lower and upper bounds. However, they are not exactly equal to those bounds, which is why the estimated bin midpoint is not truly in the middle of each bin.

You were not required to do this, but we could also parse the bin labels directly to extract the lower and upper bounds. Base R includes multiple functions for string manipulation, but I prefer to use tidyverse string manipulation found in the stringr and tidyr packages. Since the instructions specifically said to use only functions from dplyr and ggplot2 you obviously did not have to do this. The following is shown just for your reference.

Rather than using regular expressions to extract the bounds, I prefer to simplify the problem by splitting the string on a common pattern. The pred_bin labels have the lower and upper bound separated by a comma. We can thus split or separate the string on the ',' character. The tidyverse way to do this is to use the tidyr::separate() function to create additional columns within our dataframe. The resulting columns include the brackets in the bin labels, which are then removed using the stringr::str_remove() function. The last step converts the characters to numeric values. The bin midpoint is then easily calculated from the lower and upper bounds.

test_df_1_b %>% 
  group_by(pred_bin) %>% 
  summarise(num_obs = n(),
            num_events = sum(y == 'event'),
            prop_event = mean(y == 'event'),
            .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  tidyr::separate(pred_bin,
                  c("lwr_bin", "upr_bin"),
                  sep =",",
                  remove = FALSE) %>% 
  mutate(lwr_bin = stringr::str_remove(lwr_bin, "\\(|\\["),
         upr_bin = stringr::str_remove(upr_bin, "\\]")) %>% 
  mutate(across(.cols = c("lwr_bin", "upr_bin"), .fns = as.numeric)) %>% 
  mutate(bin_mid = 0.5*(lwr_bin + upr_bin)) %>% 
  select(-starts_with("num_"))

Problem 09

Calibration curves are created by executing many tedious steps. Although you had to perform those steps manually in this assignment there are existing functions which perform the necessary calculations for you. One such function is the caret::calibration() function. You will use that function in this problem to practice easily creating calibration curves. The caret::calibration() function works with resampled results, but for consistency with the previous problems, we will use with the hold-out test set predictions associated with the df_test data set.

The caret::calibration() function has 3 main arguments. The first argument is a formula, the second argument is the data set, and third is the number of bins to use. The formula follows a specific pattern:

<binary output variable> ~ <event probability variable>

The formula therefore gives the binary outcome variable name to the left of the tilde and the variable name for the event probability to the right of the tilde. These names must match the column names in the data set assigned to the data argument. The number of bins is specified by the cuts argument.

The caret::calibration() function is executed and the result is piped to xyplot() in the code chunk below. The resulting figure is consistent with the calibration curves we manually created earlier! The only difference is the xyplot() shows the event proportion and bin midpoint as percentages rather than fractions. We see the same behavior with the empirical event proportions much higher than the model 1 predictions for the first 3 bins, and the empirical proportion lower than the model 1 predictions in the next few bins.

caret::calibration(y ~ event, data = test_df_1, cuts = 10) %>% 
  xyplot()

If you were confused about the formula interface in this problem, look closely at the order presented in the formula. The y variable - the binary outcome - is the left of ~, while event - the model predicted probability - is the right of ~. The formula therefore reads as y is on the y-axis and event is on the x-axis. The formula is therefore stating what variables contribute to each axis.

Also, just to show it, the test_df_1 object can be piped into caret::calibration(). The first argument must be the formula and so we can force the piped object to be used as the second argument with the . operator, as shown below.

test_df_1 %>% 
  caret::calibration(y ~ event, data = ., cuts = 10) %>% 
  xyplot()

9c)

Create the calibration curve associated with model 8s hold-out test predictions using the caret::calibration() function. Specify the formula to be consistent with the test_df_8 data set. Assign the test_df_8 object to the data argument and assign cuts = 10. Pipe the result to the xyplot() function.

Is the created calibration curve consistent with your manually created curve from the previous problems?

SOLUTION

The calibration curve associated with model 8 is displayed below. As we can see, the xyplot() result shows all bins, even though our manually created figure did not include all bins for model 8. The calibration curve below is not wrong. However, if we only relied on this auto-generated plot, we could incorrectly determine the there are zero events when the model predicts an event probability of about 25%. This is not the case. As we saw with our manually created figure, the model does not predict probabilities below 30%! Thus, its not there is an inconsistency, its the model is not capable of of that behavior. This demonstrates that it can be useful to always check our assumptions of the behavior of an existing method!

caret::calibration(y ~ event, data = test_df_8, cuts = 10) %>% 
  xyplot()

You were not required to do this, but the code chunk below shows how to compile all three calibration curves together into a single figure.

test_df_1 %>% 
  select(y, model_1 = event) %>% 
  tibble::rowid_to_column() %>% 
  left_join(test_df_3 %>% 
              select(y, model_3 = event) %>% 
              tibble::rowid_to_column(),
            by = c("rowid", "y")) %>% 
  left_join(test_df_8 %>% 
              select(y, model_8 = event) %>% 
              tibble::rowid_to_column(),
            by = c("rowid", "y")) %>% 
  caret::calibration(y ~ model_1 + model_3 + model_8, data = ., cuts = 10) %>% 
  xyplot(auto.key = list(columns = 3))
